#!/usr/bin/env bash
set -euo pipefail

tmpfile="$(mktemp)"
trap 'rm -f "$tmpfile"' EXIT

cat >"$tmpfile" <<'EOF'
TOOLS CHEATSHEET

YAZI
  Launch:
    yazi

  Basics:
    h / l       go to parent / enter directory
    j / k       move
    g / G       top / bottom
    Space       select
    Enter       open
    q           quit

  Useful:
    .           toggle hidden files
    /           search in current list
    a           create file or directory
    d           cut
    y           copy
    p           paste
    r           rename
    x           open with chooser

  In this setup:
    files open in Neovim (LazyVim)
    hidden files are shown by default
    preview pane is enabled

LAZYGIT
  Launch:
    lazygit

  Basics:
    q           quit
    ?           keybinding help
    Tab         switch between side panel and main panel
    [ / ]       move between panels/tabs
    j / k       move
    Enter       open panel item / inspect
    Esc         back / cancel

  Common file actions:
    Space       stage or unstage selected file
    a           stage or unstage all files
    Enter       open hunk view for selected file
    c           commit staged changes
    P           push
    p           pull
    e           open selected file in Neovim

  Branches and commits:
    3           branches panel (or cycle with [ / ])
    n           new branch
    Space       checkout selected branch
    rebase / squash / fixup are available from commit views

ZELLIJ
  Launch:
    zellij                    (or ,zj [name] / ,dev from the host)

  Your setup starts in LOCKED mode. In Locked, almost every key
  passes straight through to the focused pane (nvim, shell, ...).
  Only the Alt chords below are intercepted by zellij.

  MODES
    Locked (default) app keys pass through; only Alt chords fire
    Normal           zellij's standard mode; enables the Ctrl-prefix
                     leaders (Ctrl-p Pane, Ctrl-t Tab, Ctrl-r Resize,
                     Ctrl-s Search, Ctrl-o Session)
    Pane/Tab/...     sub-modes entered from Normal via those Ctrl keys

  MODE SWITCHING
    Alt-a       toggle Locked <-> Normal
    Esc         exit a sub-mode back to Normal (without locking)

  macOS keyboard note:
    WezTerm has `send_composed_key_when_*_alt_is_pressed = false`, so
    Option+<letter> is sent as Alt+<letter> to the terminal. Every
    `Alt-x` below is just `Option+x` on the Mac. No Shift required.

  QUICK ACTIONS (work in both Locked and Normal)
    Alt-h / Alt-j / Alt-k / Alt-l   move focus left/down/up/right
    Alt-v                           split pane right
    Alt-t                           new tab
    Alt-m                           rename current tab
    Alt-p / Alt-n                   previous / next tab
    Alt-1 .. Alt-9                  jump to tab 1..9
    Alt-q                           close tab (and its panes)
    Alt-d                           detach session (see "Persistence")
    Alt-o                           toggle focused pane floating/embedded
    Alt-z                           zoom/unzoom focused pane

    Alt-f                           floating zsh (cwd-aware)
    Alt-g                           floating lazygit
    Alt-e                           floating yazi (cwd-aware)
    Alt-r                           floating scooter
    Alt-?                           floating this cheatsheet

  NORMAL-MODE DEFAULTS (after Alt-a to unlock)
    Ctrl-p      Pane sub-mode  (n new, x close, d split-down,
                                r split-right, f float, e embed, ...)
    Ctrl-t      Tab sub-mode   (n new, x close, r rename, s sync-input)
    Ctrl-r      Resize sub-mode (h/j/k/l grow, Shift+<dir> shrink)
    Ctrl-s      Scroll / Search sub-mode (e edit in nvim, s search)
    Ctrl-o      Session sub-mode (w session manager, d detach,
                                  r resurrect)

  SESSION PERSISTENCE
    Zellij saves sessions to disk and resurrects pane/tab layout
    on reattach.

      ,zj my-project        create or attach session "my-project"
      (arrange panes however you want)
      Alt-d                 detach
      ...later...
      ,zj my-project        everything restored

    Kill a specific session (including resurrection state):
      zellij delete-session my-project -y
    Nuke everything (useful when resetting):
      zellij delete-all-sessions -y

  NOTES
    pane frames are off; focus is indicated via title colour
    mouse mode is on (click to focus, drag to resize, wheel to scroll)
    default theme: Catppuccin Mocha
    web server and web sharing are disabled

WEZTERM (host-side terminal)
  Tab shortcuts (Super = Cmd on macOS):
    Super-Shift-l     switch to first tab   (Cmd+Shift+L)
    Super-Shift-d     switch to second tab  (Cmd+Shift+D)
    Super-Shift-n     switch to next tab    (Cmd+Shift+N)
    Super-Shift-p     switch to previous    (Cmd+Shift+P)
    Super-Shift-c     create tab            (Cmd+Shift+C)
    Super-Shift-r     rename current tab    (Cmd+Shift+R)
    Super-+  Super--  font size up / down
    Super-0           reset font size
    Cmd-C / Cmd-V     copy / paste (no Shift)

  Notes:
    WezTerm's default key bindings are disabled — every Option chord
    passes through to zellij inside the VM.
    config.term = "xterm-256color" so Ubuntu's terminfo is matched
    on SSH into the lima VM.
    Config: ~/.config/wezterm/wezterm.lua.

PROJECT TAB HELPERS
  "Projects" are just directories zoxide knows about — anywhere
  you've `cd`'d. Repo convention: clone via `,ghclone owner/repo` so
  everything lands under ~/code/github/<owner>/<repo>/.

    ,zdev              zoxide picker -> new tab with the `dev` layout
                       (nvim 70% / shell 30%; :q drops to shell)
    ,zagent            zoxide picker -> new tab with `dev-agentic`
                       layout (nvim 70% / ,agent 30%)
    ,zlayout <name>    zoxide picker -> new tab with a named layout
                       (see ~/.config/zellij/layouts/*.kdl)
    ,zj [name]         attach/create a zellij session (default: local)
                       Detach with Alt-d; resurrect with same name.

  PER-PROJECT LAYOUTS — TWO FLAVOURS

  1. Reusable layouts by STACK (not by project).
     Drop .kdl files under
       chezmoi/dot_config/zellij/layouts/
     e.g. rails.kdl, react.kdl, elixir.kdl. Use
       ,zlayout rails
     from any rails project. The layout describes the INITIAL pane
     arrangement. Syntax docs:
       https://zellij.dev/documentation/creating-a-layout

  2. Named sessions per PROJECT.
     Zellij resurrects sessions from disk, so state persists:
       ,zj my-rails-app      (first time: create; later: re-attach)
       (arrange panes)
       Alt-d                 (detach; zellij writes layout to disk)
       ...next time...
       ,zj my-rails-app      (same panes/tabs back)
     No .kdl authoring needed.

AI CODING HARNESSES
  The `dev-agentic` zellij layout runs `,agent` in its right pane,
  which dispatches to whichever AI coding harness is currently
  selected.

    ,agent                    launch the currently selected harness
    ,agent-select             show current + list of known harnesses
    ,agent-select <name>      persist a selection (sticks across shells)
    ,agent-select --clear     drop persistent choice; fall back to default

  One-shot override:
    AGENT_HARNESS=codex ,agent

  Available harnesses depend on repo: work installs opencode + codex;
  personal installs opencode + claude. See README for how to add more.

SCOOTER
  Launch:
    scooter

  What it is:
    interactive project-wide find/replace

  Basics:
    enter       run search from fields / apply replacements from results
    Tab         next field
    Shift-Tab   previous field
    j / k       move through matches
    Space       include or exclude current match
    a           toggle all matches
    v           multiselect mode
    e           open match in Neovim
    Ctrl-h      help
    Ctrl-r      reset back to search screen
    Ctrl-c      quit

  Useful toggles:
    Ctrl-t      include hidden files
    Alt-m       multiline search
    Alt-e       interpret escape sequences in replacement text
    Ctrl-l      toggle preview wrapping

  In this setup:
    `e` opens Neovim at the matching line and exits scooter
    syntax highlighting uses Catppuccin Mocha

NEOVIM / LAZYVIM
  Launch:
    nvim

  LazyVim ships its own keymap; press <Space> in normal mode to see
  the which-key popup with every leader binding.

  Frequently used leader bindings (default LazyVim):
    <Space>        open which-key menu
    <Space> ff     find files (Telescope)
    <Space> fg     live grep
    <Space> e      toggle file explorer (neo-tree)
    <Space> gg     open lazygit
    <Space> qq     quit all
    <Space> l      Lazy plugin manager
    <Space> cm     Mason (LSP / formatter installer)

  In this setup:
    Neovim is installed via mise on develop machines
    config lives in ~/.config/nvim (LazyVim starter)
    yazi, scooter, and lazygit open files with nvim
    arrow keys are re-enabled (LazyVim disables them by default —
      override lives in chezmoi/dot_config/nvim/lua/config/keymaps.lua)

NB (NOTES)
  nb is the host-side notes CLI.

    nb add "title"        create a new note
    nb ls                 list notes
    nb edit <id>          open in editor
    nb sync               pull + push to GitHub
    nb notebooks          list installed notebooks

  Work: notebook ~/.nb/xing  -> git@github.com:saimon-moore/nb.git
  Personal: notebook ~/.nb/home -> git@github.com:saimonmoore/nb.git

OPENSKILLS (AGENT SKILLS)
  Skills for all harnesses live in ~/.agent/skills/ and are managed
  by openskills.

    npx openskills install <src> --universal  install skill(s)
    npx openskills list                        show installed
    npx openskills update [name]              refresh from source(s)
    npx openskills remove <name>              remove a skill
    npx openskills sync -y -o ~/.agent/AGENTS.md  regen AGENTS.md

  Declarative state lives in chezmoi:
    chezmoi/dot_agent/openskills-manifest.txt
    chezmoi/dot_agent/skills/<name>/.openskills.json
  The run_onchange_after_openskills-bootstrap hook reconciles
  ~/.agent/skills with the manifest on every chezmoi apply.

HOME-SWEET-HOME HELPERS
  ,verify              host-side health check (installs / config / VM)
  ,chezmoi-init        re-apply the current machine's chezmoi state
  ,chezmoi-update      pull home-sweet-home + apply
  ,dev                 enter the dev VM (zellij session "dev")
  ,create-vm           create the Ubuntu lima VM (first time only)
  ,vm-ip               print the dev VM's IPv4 address
  ,vm-open [PORT]      open http://<vm-ip>[:PORT] in the host browser
  ,vm-cp <src> <dst>   one-shot copy host <-> VM via limactl copy.
                       Prefix VM paths with `vm:`. Good for single
                       files / small groups.
                         ,vm-cp ./file vm:~/file
                         ,vm-cp -r vm:~/build ./build
  ,vm-rsync <rsync-args> …    rsync to/from the VM via lima's SSH
                       config. All flags forward to rsync verbatim.
                         ,vm-rsync -avz --progress ./src/ vm:~/dest/
                         ,vm-rsync -avz --delete ./src/ vm:~/dest/
                         ,vm-rsync --dry-run -avz ./src vm:~/dest
                       Use over ,vm-cp for big trees, incremental
                       syncs, --delete, or any rsync flag.
  ,sync-jfrog-to-vm    (work only) copy JFrog creds into the VM

HOST <-> VM INTEGRATION

  FILE TRANSFER — QUICK REFERENCE

    ,vm-cp <src> <dst>
        One-shot copy via `limactl copy` (scp under the hood). Best
        for single files or a handful.
          ,vm-cp ./notes.md vm:~/notes.md
          ,vm-cp vm:~/build.log ./
          ,vm-cp -r ./dist vm:~/deploy

    ,vm-rsync <rsync-args> …
        rsync via lima's ssh config. All flags forward to rsync
        verbatim. Best for big trees, incremental syncs, or anything
        wanting rsync flags (--dry-run, --delete, --exclude, partial
        resume).
          ,vm-rsync -avz --progress ./my-proj/ vm:~/code/my-proj/
          ,vm-rsync -avz --delete  ./my-proj/ vm:~/code/my-proj/
          ,vm-rsync --dry-run -avz ./my-proj/ vm:~/code/my-proj/
          ,vm-rsync -avz vm:~/code/my-proj/dist/ ./dist/
          ,vm-rsync -avz --exclude 'node_modules/' --exclude '.git/' \
                    ./ vm:~/code/proj/

    Paths on both: `vm:` prefix targets the VM, anything else is a
    host path. VM paths without the prefix are just host paths —
    watch for that when shell-completing.

  FILE TRANSFER — WHEN TO USE WHICH

    Single file or handful                    ,vm-cp
    Whole directory, first time or mostly     ,vm-rsync -avz
      unchanged
    Mirror including deletions                ,vm-rsync -avz --delete
    Preview before doing anything             ,vm-rsync --dry-run -avz
    Resume an interrupted big transfer        ,vm-rsync (scp can't)

  RSYNC GOTCHA — TRAILING SLASH

    Trailing slash on the SOURCE changes semantics:
      ,vm-rsync -avz ./src/  vm:~/dest/       # contents of src/ into dest/
      ,vm-rsync -avz ./src   vm:~/dest/       # src/ itself into dest/
                                              # (you get dest/src/…)

  ESCAPE HATCH

    For raw SSH (interactive shell, port-forwarded DB, etc.):
      limactl show-ssh dev          # prints an ssh_config stanza
      limactl show-ssh --format=cmd dev   # prints a ready ssh command

  PORT FORWARDING — lima vzNAT (no manual setup needed)

    VM service binds to 127.0.0.1:PORT
      -> host reaches it at http://localhost:PORT (auto-forwarded)
    VM service binds to 0.0.0.0:PORT (incl. podman `-p PORT:PORT`
    defaults)
      -> host reaches it via http://$(,vm-ip):PORT
      -> or just run `,vm-open PORT` to open in the browser

    Prefer binding dev servers to 127.0.0.1 inside the VM — it's the
    boring path that Just Works on the host browser/curl.

  CLIPBOARD (VM -> macOS, via OSC 52)

    Anything that emits an OSC 52 escape sequence ends up on the
    macOS clipboard: nvim's "+ register, anything piped into
    `osc52-copy`. Zellij passes OSC 52 through untouched (we
    intentionally DO NOT set a zellij copy_command — setting it
    disables the passthrough).

    From nvim:
      "+y                   yank selection to system clipboard
      :set clipboard+=unnamedplus  (optional) make every y go to +
      "+p                   paste system clipboard

    From any shell command:
      echo "hello" | osc52-copy
      pbcopy-like behaviour, usable in pipelines.

    NOT included: zellij's own mouse-drag copy. Without a copy_command,
    zellij keeps mouse-selected text in its internal paste buffer only.
    Use `Alt-f` (floating shell) + a ,vm-cp one-off, or just select in
    nvim / pipe into osc52-copy instead.

    How it works:
      osc52-copy reads stdin, base64s it, and writes an OSC 52 escape
      sequence to stdout. WezTerm (host) sees the escape sequence in
      its pty stream and writes the payload to the macOS clipboard.
      zellij and lima both pass OSC 52 through transparently.

    Paste from macOS clipboard into TUI apps: normal Cmd-V works in
    WezTerm and zellij; nvim's "+p reads back via OSC 52.

  PODMAN (inside the VM)

    podman run -p 3000:3000 image             # publishes on VM 0.0.0.0
    podman run -p 127.0.0.1:3000:3000 image   # on VM localhost
                                              # -> reaches host as
                                              #    http://localhost:3000
                                              #    via vzNAT

Tip:
  Most of these tools have built-in help on ? or a visible key legend
  at the bottom.
EOF

if [[ -t 1 ]] && command -v less >/dev/null 2>&1; then
	less -R "$tmpfile"
else
	cat "$tmpfile"
fi
